Reordering the Middle East
President Bush, the Palestinian prime minister Mazen, and Israel's prime minister Sharon want to meet.
Is America serious about concluding a peace agreement between Israel and the Palestinians?
How does this meeting fit into the American Middle East strategy?
Richard Haass, head of the planning staff at the US Department of State, explains his "roadmap" for the entire Middle East.
What has been achieved in Iraq - and what the Iraqi people can now achieve with the help of the Americans - will determine the future of one of the most important countries in the Middle East.
An open, market-oriented, and peaceful Iraq could bring about reforms and growth throughout the entire region.
However, it will take some time before far-reaching changes in Iraq and throughout the entire Middle East take hold.
The challenge in Iraq after Saddam has humanitarian, security, as well as economic and political aspects.
Thanks to the advance planning by the Americans and the rest of the world, and thanks to the rapid, focused, and targeted intervention of the coalition forces during the war, the humanitarian challenge is less than anticipated.
Here and there there is a need for humanitarian aid, but the announced major crisis fortunately never materialized.
There are relatively few refugees and internally displaced persons within Iraq. Food, water, and medicine supplies are sufficient in most cases or at least improving.
The American government has made approximately 600 million dollars available through the UN and non-governmental organizations for immediate humanitarian aid.
Moreover, we must restore order in Iraq.
Security is an indispensable prerequisite for a sustainable improvement of the situation after the war. Without security, people cannot rebuild their country, cannot return to work or to schools.
After Saddam's fall, there was a wave of looting, lawlessness, and revenge.
Now it is the top priority to put an end to this violence.
In addition, it must be the task of international troops to secure and eliminate all weapons of mass destruction, prevent the violent outbreak of ethnic and religious conflicts, and ensure that none of Iraq's neighbors worsen the already fragile situation.
In the long term, we must help the Iraqis rebuild their police and military structures so that they can ensure their own security without threatening anyone.
The economic reconstruction should be viewed more as economic renewal.
The physical capital is in better condition than expected and the modern Iraq has a large reservoir of human capital.
Unlike many other post-war scenarios, there are plenty of raw materials to process in Iraq.
The USA provide more than 2 billion dollars to support the initial reconstruction efforts.
Oil production is being raised to a better level.
Among the long-term challenges are increasing oil production and reducing Iraq's enormous debt.
The decision by the UN Security Council to lift all sanctions is very welcome.
Given the many religious, ethnic, geographic, and political divisions in Iraqi society, helping with political renewal in Iraq is undoubtedly the most difficult task.
The cynics and skeptics are wrong here.
The goal of the Americans - an intact Iraq where the law is respected and the government is democratically formed - is not a fantasy, especially not because Iraq has an educated population and a quite large middle class.
The international community can achieve this goal if it is willing to continue on the chosen course and cooperate with the Iraqis until the principles of a democratic society are realized.
Responsible Iraqi leaders must be supported in order to utilize Iraq's enormous political potential for constructive decisions.
The developments in Iraq will undoubtedly have implications for the entire region, but they will not determine the fate of the Middle East.
There is hardly any foreign policy issue that engages and polarizes public opinion more strongly than the Palestinian issue.
Almost a year ago, President George W. Bush declared his goal of a democratic Palestinian state living in peaceful coexistence with Israel.
In cooperation with Russia, the EU, and the United Nations, the USA developed a plan that brings us step by step closer to this goal.
A new Palestinian government and the new prime minister represent a significant step in this direction.
Now Palestinians and Israelis must be brought together to initiate this process and take measures to improve the situation, in order to then tackle broader issues at the negotiation table.
Finally, it cannot be acceptable for terrorists to undermine the peace process forever.
However, a solution to the Palestinian issue is not automatically a solution to all the problems of the Middle East.
Clearly and unequivocally are the challenges that Iran presents to us. This country is developing weapons of mass destruction and supported terrorism.
Such actions mock the norms and rules of the international community and isolate Iran and its people.
If Iran continues in this manner, it will have consequences.
If, however, Iran turns away from terrorism and the construction of catastrophic weapons, the USA is willing to resume good relations with this country.
Just as the USA is willing to approach Syria if it manages to make substantial changes in its stance there.
A more general question is the relative lack of openness in the political and economic systems in the region.
For too long, America tolerated the "democratic exception" in the Muslim Middle East.
As long as the governments were friendly and supported regional stability, there was no reason for outsiders to advocate for a representative form of government.
We have painfully come to realize that closed political systems lead to resentment and extremism against the interests of the USA, the West, and the entire world.
Therefore, we support democracy and political reforms through the Partnership Initiative for the Middle East, launched in December 2002 by Secretary of State Colin Powell.
Closed economic systems also pose a danger.
As highlighted in last year's "Arab Human Development Report" (Report on the Development Status of Arab Countries), the Arab countries of the Middle East have remained significantly behind other regions in terms of personal freedom, women's rights, as well as economic and social development.
For too long, these countries have had to watch as the economic upturn passed them by.
President Bush is determined to share the benefits of economic freedom with the Arabs.
If his recently expressed proposal for a free trade zone between the USA and the Middle East were to be implemented within a decade, it would provide a solid foundation for such development.
